{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_378f43eb9ed34820945314c9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Contributing Guide\n2\t\n3\tThank you for contributing to APIFlask.\n4\t\n5\t\n6\t## Support questions\n7\t\n8\tPlease don't use the issue tracker for this. The issue tracker is a tool\n9\tto address bugs and feature requests in APIFlask itself. Use one of the\n10\tfollowing resources for questions about using APIFlask or issues with your\n11\town code:\n12\t\n13\t- Search with Google first using: `site:stackoverflow.com apiflask {search term, exception message, etc.}`.\n14\t- Ask on our [GitHub Discussion][_gh_discuss], create a discussion under\n15\tthe \"Q&A\" category.\n16\t- Ask on [Stack Overflow][_so].\n17\t\n18\tInclude the following information in your post:\n19\t\n20\t- Describe what you expected to happen.\n21\t- If possible, include a [minimal reproducible example][_mcve] to help us\n22\tidentify the issue. This also helps check that the issue is not with\n23\tyour own code.\n24\t- Describe what actually happened. Include the full traceback if there\n25\twas an exception.\n26\t- List your Python, Flask and APIFlask versions. If possible, check if this\n27\tissue is already fixed in the latest releases or the latest code in\n28\tthe repository.\n29\t\n30\t[_gh_discuss]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/discussions\n31\t[_so]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/apiflask?tab=Frequent\n32\t\n33\t\n34\t## Reporting issues\n35\t\n36\tIf you find a bug related to APIFlask itself, or you think APIFlask\n37\tshould provide a new feature/enhacement, feel free to create an\n38\tissue on our [issue tracker][_gh_issue].\n39\t\n40\tInclude the following information in your post:\n41\t\n42\t- Describe what you expected to happen.\n43\t- If possible, include a [minimal reproducible example][_mcve] to help us\n44\tidentify the issue. This also helps check that the issue is not with\n45\tyour own code.\n46\t- Describe what actually happened. Include the full traceback if there\n47\twas an exception.\n48\t- List your Python, Flask and APIFlask versions. If possible, check if this\n49\tissue is already fixed in the latest releases or the latest code in\n50\tthe repository.\n51\t\n52\t[_gh_issue]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/issues\n53\t[_mcve]: https://stackoverflow.com/help/minimal-reproducible-example\n54\t\n55\t\n56\t## Submitting patches\n57\t\n58\tIf there is not an open issue for what you want to submit, prefer\n59\topening one for discussion before working on a PR. You can work on any\n60\tissue that doesn't have an open PR linked to it or a maintainer assigned\n61\tto it. These show up in the sidebar. No need to ask if you can work on\n62\tan issue that interests you.\n63\t\n64\tInclude the following in your patch:\n65\t\n66\t- Include tests if your patch adds or changes code. Make sure the test\n67\tfails without your patch.\n68\t- Update any relevant docs pages and docstrings. Docs pages and\n69\tdocstrings should be wrapped at 72 characters.\n70\t- Add an entry in `CHANGES.md`. Use the same style as other\n71\tentries. Also include `Version Changed` or `Version Added` section\n72\tin relevant docstrings.\n73\t\n74\t\n75\t### First time setup\n76\t\n77\t- Download and install the latest version of Git.\n78\t- Configure git with your username and email.\n79\t\n80\t```\n81\t$ git config --global user.name 'your name'\n82\t$ git config --global user.email 'your email'\n83\t```\n84\t\n85\t- Make sure you have a GitHub account.\n86\t- Click the \"[Fork][_fork]\" button to fork APIFlask on GitHub.\n87\t- Clone your fork repository locally (replace `{username}` with your username):\n88\t\n89\t```\n90\t$ git clone https://github.com/{username}/apiflask\n91\t$ cd apiflask\n92\t$ git remote add upstream https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask\n93\t```\n94\t\n95\t- Create a virtual environment and install requirements:\n96\t\n97\tFor Linux/macOS:\n98\t\n99\t```\n100\t$ python3 -m venv env\n101\t$ source env/bin/activate\n102\t$ python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools\n103\t$ pip install -r requirements/dev.txt\n104\t$ pip install -e .\n105\t$ pre-commit install\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\tFor Windows:\n109\t\n110\t```\n111\t> python -m venv env\n112\t> env\\Scripts\\activate\n113\t> python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools\n114\t> pip install -r .\\requirements\\dev.txt\n115\t> pip install -e .\n116\t> pre-commit install\n117\t```\n118\t\n119\t[_fork]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/fork\n120\t\n121\t\n122\t### Start coding\n123\t\n124\t- Create a new branch to address the issue you want to work on (be sure to\n125\tupdate the example branch name):\n126\t\n127\t```\n128\t$ git fetch upstream\n129\t$ git checkout -b your-branch-name upstream/main\n130\t```\n131\t\n132\t- Using your favorite editor, make your changes,\n133\t[committing as you go][_commit].\n134\t- Include tests that cover any code changes you make. Make sure the\n135\ttest fails without your patch. Run the tests as described below.\n136\t- Push your commits to your fork on GitHub:\n137\t\n138\t```\n139\t$ git push --set-upstream origin your-branch-name\n140\t```\n141\t\n142\t- [Create a pull request][_pr]. Link to the issue being addressed with `fixes #123` in the pull request.\n143\t\n144\t[_commit]: https://dont-be-afraid-to-commit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/git/commandlinegit.html#commit-your-changes\n145\t[_pr]: https://docs.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/creating-a-pull-request\n146\t\n147\t\n148\t### Running the tests\n149\t\n150\tRun the basic test suite with pytest:\n151\t\n152\t```\n153\t$ pytest\n154\t```\n155\t\n156\tThis runs the tests for the current environment, which is usually\n157\tsufficient. You can run the full test suite (including checks for unit test,\n158\ttest coverage, code style, mypy) with tox:\n159\t\n160\t```\n161\t$ tox\n162\t```\n163\t\n164\t\n165\t### Building the docs\n166\t\n167\tServe the live docs with MkDocs:\n168\t\n169\t```\n170\t$ mkdocs serve\n171\t```\n172\t\n173\tYou can also build the HTML docs to preview:\n174\t\n175\t```\n176\t$ mkdocs build\n177\t```\n178\t\n179\tOpen ``site/index.html`` in your browser to view the docs.\n180\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2c1b239f-26bf-4642-97fe-26d2a26be742","uuid":"49bb0bd5-2fa5-4446-b894-9e07c3d48f2f","timestamp":"2026-04-08T20:43:40.105Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md","content":"# Contributing Guide\n\nThank you for contributing to APIFlask.\n\n\n## Support questions\n\nPlease don't use the issue tracker for this. The issue tracker is a tool\nto address bugs and feature requests in APIFlask itself. Use one of the\nfollowing resources for questions about using APIFlask or issues with your\nown code:\n\n- Search with Google first using: `site:stackoverflow.com apiflask {search term, exception message, etc.}`.\n- Ask on our [GitHub Discussion][_gh_discuss], create a discussion under\nthe \"Q&A\" category.\n- Ask on [Stack Overflow][_so].\n\nInclude the following information in your post:\n\n- Describe what you expected to happen.\n- If possible, include a [minimal reproducible example][_mcve] to help us\nidentify the issue. This also helps check that the issue is not with\nyour own code.\n- Describe what actually happened. Include the full traceback if there\nwas an exception.\n- List your Python, Flask and APIFlask versions. If possible, check if this\nissue is already fixed in the latest releases or the latest code in\nthe repository.\n\n[_gh_discuss]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/discussions\n[_so]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/apiflask?tab=Frequent\n\n\n## Reporting issues\n\nIf you find a bug related to APIFlask itself, or you think APIFlask\nshould provide a new feature/enhacement, feel free to create an\nissue on our [issue tracker][_gh_issue].\n\nInclude the following information in your post:\n\n- Describe what you expected to happen.\n- If possible, include a [minimal reproducible example][_mcve] to help us\nidentify the issue. This also helps check that the issue is not with\nyour own code.\n- Describe what actually happened. Include the full traceback if there\nwas an exception.\n- List your Python, Flask and APIFlask versions. If possible, check if this\nissue is already fixed in the latest releases or the latest code in\nthe repository.\n\n[_gh_issue]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/issues\n[_mcve]: https://stackoverflow.com/help/minimal-reproducible-example\n\n\n## Submitting patches\n\nIf there is not an open issue for what you want to submit, prefer\nopening one for discussion before working on a PR. You can work on any\nissue that doesn't have an open PR linked to it or a maintainer assigned\nto it. These show up in the sidebar. No need to ask if you can work on\nan issue that interests you.\n\nInclude the following in your patch:\n\n- Include tests if your patch adds or changes code. Make sure the test\nfails without your patch.\n- Update any relevant docs pages and docstrings. Docs pages and\ndocstrings should be wrapped at 72 characters.\n- Add an entry in `CHANGES.md`. Use the same style as other\nentries. Also include `Version Changed` or `Version Added` section\nin relevant docstrings.\n\n\n### First time setup\n\n- Download and install the latest version of Git.\n- Configure git with your username and email.\n\n```\n$ git config --global user.name 'your name'\n$ git config --global user.email 'your email'\n```\n\n- Make sure you have a GitHub account.\n- Click the \"[Fork][_fork]\" button to fork APIFlask on GitHub.\n- Clone your fork repository locally (replace `{username}` with your username):\n\n```\n$ git clone https://github.com/{username}/apiflask\n$ cd apiflask\n$ git remote add upstream https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask\n```\n\n- Create a virtual environment and install requirements:\n\nFor Linux/macOS:\n\n```\n$ python3 -m venv env\n$ source env/bin/activate\n$ python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools\n$ pip install -r requirements/dev.txt\n$ pip install -e .\n$ pre-commit install\n```\n\nFor Windows:\n\n```\n> python -m venv env\n> env\\Scripts\\activate\n> python -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools\n> pip install -r .\\requirements\\dev.txt\n> pip install -e .\n> pre-commit install\n```\n\n[_fork]: https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/fork\n\n\n### Start coding\n\n- Create a new branch to address the issue you want to work on (be sure to\nupdate the example branch name):\n\n```\n$ git fetch upstream\n$ git checkout -b your-branch-name upstream/main\n```\n\n- Using your favorite editor, make your changes,\n[committing as you go][_commit].\n- Include tests that cover any code changes you make. Make sure the\ntest fails without your patch. Run the tests as described below.\n- Push your commits to your fork on GitHub:\n\n```\n$ git push --set-upstream origin your-branch-name\n```\n\n- [Create a pull request][_pr]. Link to the issue being addressed with `fixes #123` in the pull request.\n\n[_commit]: https://dont-be-afraid-to-commit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/git/commandlinegit.html#commit-your-changes\n[_pr]: https://docs.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/creating-a-pull-request\n\n\n### Running the tests\n\nRun the basic test suite with pytest:\n\n```\n$ pytest\n```\n\nThis runs the tests for the current environment, which is usually\nsufficient. You can run the full test suite (including checks for unit test,\ntest coverage, code style, mypy) with tox:\n\n```\n$ tox\n```\n\n\n### Building the docs\n\nServe the live docs with MkDocs:\n\n```\n$ mkdocs serve\n```\n\nYou can also build the HTML docs to preview:\n\n```\n$ mkdocs build\n```\n\nOpen ``site/index.html`` in your browser to view the docs.\n","numLines":180,"startLine":1,"totalLines":180}}}
